title: For Sale/Trade:  Early Chinese SKS 'Ghost Rifle'
postcontent:
This model of sks was the very first produced in China with help from Russia. These guns were made out of Russian parts and are high quality. This particular gun has a mismatched trigger group with a Russian serial number, and the sight also has Russian markings on it. There are a few other early Chinese proof markings along the barrel as well. All other numbers match with a 6 digit serial. What is interesting about these types of rifles is the lack of arsenal stamp, which is why many refer to them as 'Ghost Rifles'
This gun does have a arsenal repaired crack, but it is fully functional. I have decided not to replace the stock because I enjoy the originality and the trench art.

title: For Sale:  12 Gauge Hulls - Once Fired - 2,500 or 3,000
postcontent:
I started skeet shooting at our farm last summer with a few friends... And we were out there a lot, every weekend and occasionally during the week as well.

And since I wanted to get into reloading, I always gathered and kept the "empties". But, that just never happened and since I'll be moving in a few months, I'm looking to find a new home for these hulls.

They're almost exclusively 12 gauge, but there are a handful (couple dozen maybe) of 20 gauge and .410 in there as well. Like I said tho, 98% or more are 12 gauge.

Almost all of them are Remington or Federal, with a few from various other names. 

There are 5 crates of them. How big are the crates, you ask? They used to hold 135 clays, each.

I picked an averagly-full crate and started counting. I got to 200 and it was still at least 2/3 full, thus I'm estimating there are 2,500 to 3,000 hulls here in total.

They're all once-fired and have been stored out of the weather.

Ballistic Products sells once-fired winchesters for 10 cents a piece. As mentioned, these are mostly Federal's and Remington's, so I'm asking $250obo for the lot cash or

Price negotiable, also willing to trade for 7.62x54R, 7.62x39 or 5.45x39 (7N6 only). Cash preferred.

It is estimated that Around 85% of these were purchased as private sidearm use by mainly Union Civil War officers and Soldiers and a few to Confederate Soldiers there is also several sets known to have been presented to Confederate Officers in recognition ceremonies. Writeup per AO Site:
The Thompson Custom 1911 frames are machined on high precision computerized machinery from a 420 stainless steel casting. The slide is machined from a solid stainless steel billet utilizing specialized tooling to reduce set-up and refixturing. The combination of high precision equipment and fewer set-ups result in a higher quality and more consistent final product at a lower price.

The slide and frame are finished in an attractive matte finish, markings are laser-engraved including the distinctive Thompson bullet logo on the slide. Front and rear sights are black with serrations and are dovetailed into the slide. The ejection port is flared and the slide has front and rear serrations machined at a slight angle. The mainspring housing is checkered and the frontstrap is machine checkered at 20 lines per inch. Additional features include an adjustable trigger, combat hammer, stainless steel, full-length recoil guide rod, extended beavertail grip safety; extended magazine release; checkered laminate grips with a Thompson bullet logo inlay and a checkered slide stop lever.
